We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presentation of the child suggests Erb’s palsy, which affects the upper trunk of the brachial plexus. The muscles that are most commonly affected in Erb’s palsy are the deltoid, supraspinatus, infraspinatus, and biceps. Among the options, triceps is not affected and should have normal strength.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The description of the right arm adducted and internally rotated at the shoulder and extended at the elbow suggests an injury to the brachial plexus, specifically the upper trunk. This would affect the musculocutaneous nerve, which innervates brachialis and brachioradialis muscles, and the musculocutaneous and radial nerves which innervate the biceps muscle. The triceps muscle, which is innervated by the radial nerve, would likely have normal strength.
